    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="498"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d498">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName> and Prime
                        Minister <persName>Churchill</persName> to Marshal <persName type="to"
                            >Stalin</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d498fn1">Sent to the War Cabinet Office in London as
                        Churchill’s telegram No. <gloss target="#t_Welfare1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Welfare</hi>
                        </gloss> 217 and forwarded to the British Ambassador in the Soviet Union
                        (Clark Kerr). Concerning the delivery of this message in Moscow, see <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1062">p. 1062</ref>, fn.
                        1.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">most secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <gloss target="#t_Quadrant1">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Quadrant</hi>
                            </gloss>
                        </placeName>, [<date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-19">August 19,
                            1943</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>President and Prime Minister to Marshal Stalin. Most Secret and Personal.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d498fn2">For the paragraphs of this message omitted here, see
                            <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1062">p.
                        1062</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <list>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>To turn to another subject, following on the decisions at <gloss
                            target="#t_Trident1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Trident</hi>
                        </gloss>, His Majesty’s Government entered upon negotiations with the
                        Portuguese in order to obtain naval and Air facilities in <gloss
                            target="#t_Lifebelt1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lifebelt</hi>
                        </gloss> (see our immediately following telegram<note n="3" xml:id="d498fn3"
                            >In telegram No. <gloss target="#t_Welfare1">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Welfare</hi>
                            </gloss> 218 (<hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1063">p.
                                1063</ref>) it was explained that this code name “refers to
                            Portuguese Atlantic islands.”</note>). Accordingly, His Majesty’s
                        Ambassador at Lisbon<note n="4" xml:id="d498fn4">Sir Ronald Hugh
                            Campbell.</note> invoked the Anglo-Portuguese Alliance, which has lasted
                        600 years unbroken,<note n="5" xml:id="d498fn5">See <hi rend="italic"
                                >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_611">p. 611</ref>, fn. 3.</note> and
                        invited the Portuguese to grant the said facilities. Dr. Salazar was of
                        course oppressed by the fear of German bombing out of revenge, and of
                        possible hostile movements by the Spaniards. We have accordingly furnished
                        him with supplies of anti-aircraft artillery and fighter airplanes which are
                        now in transit, and we have also informed Dr. Salazar that should Spain
                        attack Portugal we shall immediately declare war on Spain and render <pb
                            facs="1206" n="1092" xml:id="pg_1092"/> such help as is in our power. We
                        have not however made any precise military convention ear-marking particular
                        troops as we do not think either of these contingencies probable. Dr.
                        Salazar has now consented to the use of <gloss target="#t_Lifebelt1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lifebelt</hi>
                        </gloss> by the British, with Portuguese collaboration, in the early part of
                            October.<note n="6" xml:id="d498fn6">See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>,
                                <ref target="#pg_614">p. 614</ref>, fn. 2.</note> As soon as we are
                        established there and he is relieved from his anxieties, we shall press for
                        the extension of these facilities to the United States ships and
                        aircraft.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>The possession of <gloss target="#t_Lifebelt1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lifebelt</hi>
                        </gloss> is of great importance to the sea war. The <gloss
                            target="#t_Uboat1">U–boat</gloss>s have quitted the North Atlantic,
                        where convoys have been running without loss since the middle of May, and
                        have concentrated more on the southern route. The use of <gloss
                            target="#t_Lifebelt1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lifebelt</hi>
                        </gloss> will be of the utmost service in attacking them from the Air.
                        Besides this, there if [<hi rend="italic">is</hi>] the ferrying of United
                        States heavy bombers to Europe and Africa, which is also most
                        desirable.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>All of the above is of the most especially secret operational
                        character.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
